{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958050901/0260.xml":{"full_text":"THE UNION JOURNAL\u2019S\na\nEditorial Page\nFriday, May 9,1958\nMail Call!\nWHEN\nVV mere\nthe Ohio Chamber of Com\nmerce announced its campaign to\ncirculate petitions for its open-shop law,\nLabor believed that many people would\nbe sent petitions without asking for them\nand that many others might not under\nstand the seriousness of the issue and be\ncome unknowing partners to the scheme.\nSo, a policy was adopted of contact\ning the people who were listed at the Sec\nretary of State\u2019s office as circulators and\ninforming them of the real purpose of\nsuch a law and of the real sponsors of the\npetition campaign.\nWe call your attention to two recent\nletters which support Labor\u2019s policy of in\nforming circulators of the real issues at\nstake. One was written to the Secretary\nof State by W L. Borchers of the Borch\ners Insurance Co., Dayton.\n\u201cI have been advised that my name\nhas been entered on the State records\nas a solicitor for the Right To Work\npetition,\u201d Borchers wrote. \u201cPlease be\nadvised that I am questioning how my\nname has been submitted as I have\nnever authorized anyone to use my\nname in connection with the Right To\nWork petition.\nBorchers also wrote that if \u201cmy sig\nnature has been used in connection with\nthe above, please be advised it has been\nforged.\u201d\nThe other letter was written by P. E.\nHouser, personnel director of the Union\nChain and Manufacturing Co., Sandusky.\nHouser, who is circulating a petition, was\nasked by the Sandusky Industrial Union\nCouncil to debate the \u201cright-to-work\u201d is\nsue.\nHouser declined the invitation because\n\"I am afraid that I could very easily be\nembarrassed as I must admit quite\nfrankly, I have not had the opportunity\nto study the pros and cons of this par\nticular subject.\u201d And he concluded his let\nter:\n\u201cPlease pass my regrets along to the\nmembers of your council and perhaps the\noccasion may arise again but involving a\nsubject on which I am qualified to dis\ncuss.\u201d\nThese letters prove that people have\nbeen receiving petitions without request\ning them and others are circulating peti\ntions on an issue they know nothing\nabout.\nSo, the next time the Chamber of\nCommerce cries about \u201cintimidating\u201d cir\nculators, you will know that the crying\nis just another part of their campaign\nto hide the facts.\nComments on\nthe Press\nS OUR PUBLIC service effort for the\nweek we would like to pass on some\nA\ncomments about American newspapers\nfrom Henry Steel Commager, the noted\nAmerican historian and author.\nIn a talk at the University of Michi\ngan, Commager outlined four areas where\nthe press fails in its role of informing and\neducating readers:\n1. \u201cWith few exceptions, the press\nover-emphasizes local news at the\nexpense of regional, national and in\nternational news.\u201d\n2. \"The press has a tendency to go\nin for sensational rather than signifi\ncant news. A newspaper which gives\nfront-page headlines to the outcome of\na high school football game is not a\nvery responsible paper.\u201d\n3. \u201cThe press is responsible in part\nfor the non-intellectualism of our day.\nIt gives less space to art, literature, mu\nsic and drama than most papers\nabroad.\u201d\n4. \u201cEditorial policy is almost al\nways namby-pamby. Our papers don\u2019t\nstand for anything, revealing the tim\nidity and adaptability which is the\ncurse of Americans at the present time.\u201d\nFor the most part, Commager said,\n\u201cthe press is partisan in its presentation\nof the news\u201d and \u201chas ignored infrac\ntions of important civil rights except\nwhere those infractions have touched the\npress directly.\u201d\nCommager said that one of the prob\n~ORGAMZE~TOLEDO 100%~~\nOfficial Publication of Organized Labor\nin Northwestern Ohio\nGrand\nAward\nWinner\nKaUnt at Toledo, Ohio, Post Office as second\nclass natter under the act of Aug. 24, 1912\nPublished Every Friday\nPublishing Office, 425 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\n4\nFoe information Phone CH. 1-9126\nWalter Murphy\nBernard Stern\nWilliam Berden\nDerele Collins\nMelvin Zimkowski,\nEdmond A. Pawlleht\nEditor\nAssociate Editor\nSports Editor\nCirculation Manager\nJournal Cameramen\nWalter Murphy, Charles Ballard,\nOtto Beebe (Local 348) Board of Trustees\nDave Huber\nDirector of Advertising\nTelephone Advertising Department\nCH. 4-4400 and CH. 6-1141\nMember Trade Union Advei\nN. X.\n\nlems today is the \u201cspectacular decline of\nstatesmanship in our country. An explan*\nation is that the press considers private\nenterprise at a premium and continually\npreaches to our young about public en\nterprise.\u201d And please note this statement:\n\u201cEthics of politics in the U. S. have\nalmost always been higher than business\nethics. The press is not giving a fair pic\nture of the last Administration or the\npresent one because of its special inter\nest in this area.\u201d\nCommager\u2019s comments are not true of\nall newspapers, of course, but unfortu\nnately they are true enough about most\npapers to permit such a general con\ndemnation.\nHow's YOUR Aide?\nFollowing is from President Eisen\nhower\u2019s press conference of April 23:\n\u201cQuestion: Sit, for some time you\nhave been advising the American people\non the recession to get out of it by buy\ning. I am wondering if you could tell us,\nsir, what purchases you have made your\nself and what sort of things you may be\nbuying?\n\u201cThe President: Do you want to go\nsee my personal aide, who buys my\nthings? I don\u2019t know.\u201d\nOK everybody, let\u2019s get our aides on\nthe ball and get this recession over with!\nVandercook Says:\nPRICES, WE HAVE once more monotonously\nbeen informed, are still going up. With the\ncollective vacant smile with which the Admini\nstration seems to accept all bad economic news,\nthat phenomenon, too, is being treated as if it\nwere something like sun spots, or tornadoes.\nAs something, at any rate, over which mortal\nmen have no possible control.\nConservative politicians and economists\ncluck their tongues and admit that it is,indeed,\nodd that in a time of diminishing national in\ncome and of rising unemployment the cost of\nliving has again climbed to an all-time high.\nYet, few voices have been raised to point out\nthe immense seriousness of those paradoxical\nprice increases, to note the disagreeable fact\nthat, in this time of test, the economic System\nunder which we live is failing to perform its\nchief responsibility.\nRight now, in the USA, the competitive\nsystem is making a minimum effort to be\ngenuinely competitive. The free enterprisers\nhave quit, in droves, almost all effort to be\nenterprising. It is the hardheads, and not the\neggheads, who appear to believe that the law\nof supply and demand can be repealed\u2014by\nprice fixing, by secret trade agreements, by\nplain obstinacy.\nA number of years ago when Clement Att\nlee was Socialist Prime Minister of Great Bri\ntain I asked him whether it was the long-range\npurpose of Brithish Socialism to nationalize\npractically all industries. This was his reply:\n\u201cEmphatically not. It is only when private in\ndustries become monopolistic, when they cease\nto.be truly competitive, that we feel they\nmight better be administered by the state\nit\u2019s become a fair question, when prices\nin the U.S. during 16 out of 19 months have\nkept on rising, whether American business\nis not Inviting what none of us wants, just\nAttlee\u2019s kind of criticism.\nBy cutting down production, big business\nappears to think a shortage will, eventually,\nbe created. Then, they imagine, those surplus\ncars will find buyers. High unit profits will\nin some measure compensate for smaller sales\nby saving the pay of those workers who have\nbeen laid off; corporate losses will be lessened.\nThat way of doing things, which seems to\nbe the only explanation for the extraordinary\npersistence of high prices, is a policy of eco\nnomic scarcity. In a nation which has commit\nted itself by impulse, by custom, and even by\nlaw, to an economy of abundance\nstill a lot of money around.\nthere is\nMany wise Americans at all income levels\nhave accumulated impressive savings, but,\nnaturally, they are now waiting for the wind\nof prices to be tempered to the shorn economy,\nfor the bargains we are not yet getting!\nThrough The Years\nWith The Toledo Union Journal\nFIFTEEN TEARS AGO\nMAT 14, 1943: A program of economic re\ntreat and appeasement which has marked La\nbor's conduct for the past year, must be re\nplaced by a definite stand and fight for eco\nnomic stabilization was the conclusion re\nsuiting from a UAW-CIO regional conference\nheld in Columbus Local 12 will cooperate\nwith the request of the International UAW\nin forming consumer committees to watch\nprices in the retail stores of Toledo, and will\nreport and ask for prosecution of all those\nwho violate ceiling prices or in any other\nmanner act to defeat the purpose which the\nOffice of Price Administration was created\nCorporation profits for 1942 after taxes\nwere 80% higher than the prewar 1939 level,\nthe Labor Research Association reports.\nTEN TEARS AGO\nMAT 14, 1948: Support of Toledo UAW\nCIO local unions was pledged to striking em\nployees of the Chrysler Corp, this week fol\nlowing a walkout of the corporation's 75,000\nworkers. Efforts of Federal mediators failed\nto bring agreement between the union and\ncompany During 30 days in March the\nNLRB received more cases and conducted\nmore elections than in any previous month\nin its history.\nFIVE TEARS AGO\nMAY 13, 1933: The four top officers of Lo\ncal 12 are unopposed for re-election for the\n1953 term. Members attending one of the larg\nest meetings in months said it is in recogni\ntion for outstanding work, untiring hours, and\ninterest to serve the membership to the best\nof their ability For the first quarter of\nthe year General Motors Corp, reported net\nsales of $2,546,834,722 and a net profit of\n$151,261,876. For the first quarter of last year\nG. M. reported a net profit of $127,023,260.\n\u201cUnited We Stand\u201d\nA\n\n17%\n0*\n\n3\n\ni\n3\n4\n\n4\n1\nCO\n1\n\nCB\ni\nA\n\nI\n\nUi\nitti\nP\ns\nsi\nI\n4\n\nw*\n\nThink It Over\nGap\nummMM\nA Crushing Responsibility\nBy PETE ZVARA\nMnnmmmmonflef\"l*r\nIaAHTTWDAM/(\"\"*\"AM*AHTMOPAE1\nIT IS NOT very often that one is given the\nopportunity to participate in the making\nof history. Such opportunity was the lot this\nweek of the delegates who attended the Ohio\nAFL and CIO state conventions to bring about\nthe formal merger of the two\ngreat and powerful organiza\ntions.\nThe new merged organi\nzation, we are told, numbers\nsomething like one million\ntrade union members\u2014a tre\nmendous organization that\nreaches into the very heart of\nalmost every industry in our\nstate.\nI say almost every indus\ntry, since the workers who\nman the coal industry and\nPete Zvara\nmost of the railroads belong to -organizations\nthat are still outside the giant AFL-CIO federa\ntion. Perhaps soon, we hope, these organiza\ntions too will join the Main Camp of Labor,\nthus uniting all factions of the organized labor\nmovement in one giant federation where they\nreally belong.\nHowever, be that as it may, we can say that\nright now the newly-merged Ohio AFL-CIO\nstate organization is by far the most powerful\norganization of its kind in our history. Cer\ntainly never before have we had such a huge\ncentrally directed organization in Ohio. And\nit's about time that our two state organizations\ngot together.\nFor in Ohio we need the services of such a\npowerful state organization, perhaps more so\nthan in any other state in the Union. This as\nsumption is justified, I believe, if we recog\nnize the fact that (outside the Dixiecrat states)\nnowhere, in no other state, does the state gov\nernment treat the labor movemen with greater\ndisdain than we are treated in the Buckeye\nstate.\nThis, mind you, despite the fact that our\ntrade union membership tops the one million\nmark.\nWell, how do we explain this disgraceful\nsituation?\nBEFORE THE turbulent days of the Great\nDepression and the New Deal, the Organized\nLabor Movement in Ohio, as elsewhere, was\ntoo small to have much of a political influence\non either the state or federal governments.\nHowever, following the election of Frank\nlin D. Roosevelt in 1932, and his assumption of\noffice in March of 1933, the industrial work\ners of our country\u2014including those in Ohio\u2014\nbegan to organize in huge numbers.\nAnd in this tremendous organizational up\nheaval, Ohio workers were in the vanguard\neverywhere. Yes, some of the most glorious\nchapters of our labor movement were written\nby Ohio workers. And that against the most\nvicious, most violent type of opposition. This\nwas so in years immediately proceeding and\nthen following the formation of the C.I.O. in\nthe fall of 1935 in Atlantic City, N.J.\nFOR EXAMPLE, who can forget the Incre\ndible courage and determination of the Elec\ntric Auto-Lite workers in Toledo who battled\nevery form of opposition that the employers\nand the state government could throw against\nthem, including the Ohio National Guard.\nIn this fight alone, a fight that laid the solid\nIMNnmmMmmr*dmCmICme*mGGGO/GNIaBRAARTPWMTNMTNORATTIUHt\nfoundations of the Labor Movement in Toledo,\nhundreds were arrested, scores were injured\nand two workers were killed outright.\nIn the gigantic struggles to compel the ar\nrogant rulers of the Auto and Rubber indus\ntries, Ohio workers in Cleveland, in Akron and\nother communities were in the very forefront\nof the often bloody struggles to compel corpor\nations to recognize their unions.\nOr who can forget the fight of Ohio's steel\nworkers in the Little Steel Strike that took\nplace in the summer of 1937? Once again, in\nthe bloody clashes that raged in the steeltowns\nof Ohio, the employers were given temporary\nvictory over the steel workers by means of\nthe Ohio National Guard, assisted by local po\nlice and deputy sheriffs everywhere.\nYes, we could cite examples almost end\nlessly, each more inspiring, more glorious than\nthe other, to show the courage and determina\ntion of the workers in Ohio as they battled for\ntheir unions against any and all opposition.\nBriefly, this is the story of our Labor Move\nment in Ohio on the economic field.\nBut what happened to us on the political\nfield?\nI SAID ABOVE that the state government,\nat the moment the O\u2019Neill Republican Admini\nstration, almost completely ignores our move\nment and our wishes. Surely the treatment of\nS.U.B. by Gov. O\u2019Neill is a classic and shock\ning example.\nOnly in three other states\u2014Indiana, Vir\nginia and North Carolina\u2014does the state ad\nministration treat their workers with equal\ncontempt. For what else can you call this treat\nment? This treatment that deprives workers\nof millions of dollars that is rightfully theirs\nunder legally negotiated labor-management\ncontracts?\nAnd who can deny that our Unemployment\nand Workman\u2019s Compensation laws are among\nthe worst in the country?\nFurther, who can deny that our delegation\nto the U. S. Congress\u2014the Senate and the\nHouse\u2014is just as reactionary in the main as\nis the majority of our General Assembly in\nColumbus?\nAnd, mind -you, this in one of the foremost\nindustrial states in our country\u2014this in a state\nwhere the combined Labor Movement has well\nover one million members.\nTruly, we should be ashamed of ourselves!\nFORTUNATELY, with our merged AFL\nCIO at the helm, the future looks bright. For\nthere is not the slightest doubt in anyone\u2019s\nmind, but that our newly elected leadership\u2014\nbacked by our membership\u2014has the necessary\ncourage and intelligence to lead us into politi\ncal struggles that will bring us the kind of vic\ntory on the political field that we are accus\ntomed to achieving in our economic struggles.\nSurely it is a disgrace that in Twentieth\nCentruy America one anillion trade unionists\nin Ohio are treated like politically second\nclass citizens. More, unless we put a stop to\ntheir diabolical plans, they will treat us\u2014\nthrough their Right to Scab Law\u2014as little\nmore than industrial serfs.\nSo, the job ahead for our membership\nfor our new leadership is, indeed, enormous.\nTruly we can say that the mandate issued by\nthis convention places upon all of us a crush\ning responsibility.\nLetters To The Editor\n\n1\nHelping Hand\nTO THE EDITOR;\nThis is probably an unusual\nrequest, but I read in the\nunion paper about one of\nAuto-Lite\u2019s former employes,\nRobert Miller. The article re\nferred to how hard it was for\nhim to get along on his unem\nployment compensation check.\nI was hoping I could help\nin some small way, if you send\nme his home address. He lives\nin Ravine Park Village and\nhas nine children.\nMRS. C. L. WRIGHT,\n3535 Somerset Street,\nLincoln 4, Nebraska\n\nt\n(This letter has been turned\nover to the Auto-Lite shop\ncommittee. The article re\nferred to by this Nebraska\nreader appeared in the Febru\nary 28 issue of the Union Jour\nnal. It wa\u00bb written by Mari\nene Valiquette of the Journal\nstaff about the hardthipt of\nthe Robert Miller family of 12\nRavine Park Village. The Ed\nitor.!\nTheme Song?\nTO THE EDITOR:\nI contribute this verse,\n\u201cAFL-CIO\", to the labor\nmovement. It is my own or\niginal work. It could easily\nbecome the theme song of the\nlabor merger, sung to the\ntune of MOTHER.\ns\nA is for our great affiliation,\nF\u2019s for friends and friends\nwe\u2019ll always be,\nL's for labor\u2019s closed shop and\nmill-elation,\nC is for the closed shop cen\ntury,\nI's for the independence we\nare winning,\nO means one and one we\u2019ll\never be.\nPut them all together.\nThey spell AFL-CIO,\nA word that means the world\nto me.\nYou\u2019ve never heard of me\nbut maybe dad\u2019s name rings\na bell; Gene Raymond, Sr.\nHe was associated with Doe\nReedy and Gene Debs in the\nold days.\nGENE RAYMOND, JR.\n1086 Avondale Dr.\nt\nPress Strangely Silent\nOn Recession Report\nBy BARROW LYONS\nSpecial to the Union Journal\nWASHINGTON\u2014One of the strangest failures of the press\nto report important news relating to the current recession oc\ncurred here last week.\nThe news consisted of testimony before the Senate Finance\nCommittee by one of America's leading economists charging that\nbungling by the Federal Reserve Board contributed largely to\nthe recession. This ordinarily would be front page headline news.\nThe top-ranking economist who testified was Seymour Har\nris, chairman of the Economics-Department, Harvard Univer\nsity. His statement was sensational.\nYet the New York Times overlooked it entirely, and the\nWall Street Journal carried only a brief sentence on it in a\nround-up column.\nIt was the first time that an outstanding economist had\ngiven before a committee of Congress so forthright a statement\nexplaining the bad days that have come upon the nation.\nAlthough even the summary statement is too long to publish\nhere, it appears to be so important that extensive excerpts are\ngiven below:\nCauses Of The Depression\nUndoubtedly the investment boom was an important factor.\nIn 11 years the country expanded its plants, equipment, and\ninventories by $413 billion. Excess capacity is a threat though\nit is relative.\nRestrictive monetary policy contributed to the decline.\nThe Federal Reserve raised rates and curtailed monetary ex\npansion in 1956 and 1957 far below the amounts required by\na growing economy.\nThis restricted monetary policy is reflected in the reduced\nstimulus given by consumer and housing credits in successive\nyears.\nThese dropped from $20.8 billions in 1955 to $18.1 billion\nin 1956, and $14.3 billion in 1957.\nA turnover from deficit financing to substantial surpluses\nalso helped bring on a reversal\u2014from a stimulating factor that\nis adding to spending, governmental finance had become a\ndepressive factor, that is reducing spending and paying off debt\nThe figures: Cash income and outgo of the Federal Govern\nment, in 1955 a deficit of $729 million; in 1956 a surplus of\n$5,525 million; and in 1957 a surplus of $1,194 million.\nFailure Of Monetary Policy\nDespite a vigorous policy, the Federal Reserve failed to stop\nthe inflation and yet helped bring on a recession.\nExcessive emphasis on the objective of an absolutely stable\ndollar\u2014and emphasis also favored by the Administration\u2014led\nto this debacle. The goal of growth was rather neglected. Why\nthe failure?\nFinally, to stabilise prices with a large cost inflation could\nonly be done by inducing unemployment through a restrictive\nmonetary policy. This the Federal Reserve accomplished.\nTHERAPY: The spending of the private economy is run\nning down at the rate of 10 to 15 billions per year. New spend\ning must be injected by the Government at an annual rate, or\nat a lower rate if we allow for secondary effects of new spend\ning or tax cuts. This is a condition for stopping the decline.\nMonetary Policy\nWe expect a much greater lift here. The reserves and the\nexcess reserves of member banks are much below what they\nought to be.\nWhat is the Federal Reserve afraid of? They should pur\nchase several billions of Government securities as a means of\nincreasing the supply of money and ultimately depressing in\nterest rates\u2014a must for recovery.\nThe policy of selling long term Government securities in\nthe midst of a recession is foolish and costly and should be\nstopped at once and for all. These securities compete with pri\nvate enterprise and keep rates up.\nEXPENDITURE POLICY: We propose a spending program\nof $4 billion for calendar year 1958 above budgetary requests\nof January. In listing the items, we take account of congressional\naction and trends so far, of the need of more security outlays,\nand the wisdom of doubling outlays on hospitals, urban rede\nvelopment and public housing. We also propose a rise of one\nthird in spending on natural resources and a $1 billion program\nfor educational construction.\nI\nTax Policy\nI prefer a spending to a tax reduction policy. The former\nfavors especially those in need and yields larger results per\ndollar of cost to the Treasury than an equivalent tax reduction.\nBut tax cuts give quicker results, and we need immediate\nresponses if we are to stop a snowballing of the decline.\nHence I urge a $3 billion tax cut for 6 months in 1958 (to\nbe extended if necessary). My choice of alternatives is a split\nting of the rate on the first $2,000 of taxable income\u201410 percent\non the first $1,000 and 20 percent on the next $1,000. What is\nneeded is a lift in consumption and this type of tax remission\nshould contribute to that.\nIN GENERAL: We propose a really cheap money policy,\na rise in spending of $4 billion, and a cut of taxes of $3 billion\nin calendar 1958. Against a deficit in calendar 1958 of about\n$3-4 billion, the total gross deficit would then rise to about $10\nbillion.\nBut at present incomes this is equivalent to less than half\nof the annual deficits in the 1930\u2019s. What is more these expendi\ntures and tax cuts should be largely, if not wholly, offset by\nadditional tax receipts and not to mention the need of publie\nassets and services which would be made available.\n1\nBulletin Board\nSaturday, May 16\nKIDS PARTY 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nE. W. BLISS 1:30 P.M. Parlor A\nSTEEL TUBE 10:00 A.M. Parlor B\nPETERS STAMPING 9:00 A.M. Parlor C\nSunday, May 11\nSKILLED TRADES 1:00 P.M. Parlor A\nMonday, May 12\nBARRETT 10:00 A.M.' Parlor A\nBARRETT 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nBARRETT STEWARDS 9:00 A.M. Parlor B\nBARRETT STEWARDS 7:00 P.M. Parlor B\nSAVE ELECTRIC 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nTuesday, May 13\n1\nSURFACE COMB. 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nBARON STEEL 7:30 P.M. Parlor C\nTOLEDO SCALE ENGINEERS\u20148:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor H\nWednesday, May 14\nJ&L 7:00 P.M. Parlor A\nJ&L 12:00 P.M. Parlor B\nSUPEIOR SPINNING 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nRANSOM RANDOLPH 7:30 P.M. Parlor C\nThursday, May 15\nPENSION CLUB\nCARD PARTY 12:30 P.M. Parlor A 1\nPIPE THREADING 7:30 P.M. Parlor A\nVICTOR SCREW 8:00 P.M. Board Room\nPORCELAIN 7:30 P.M. Parlor C\nCAMERA CLUB 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nCAMP COUNSELORS 7:00 P.M. Parlor H\nODLAND, STD. TOOL, WATSON\nWELEVER, McCOLL, TOTH 8:00 P.M. 4th Floor\nFriday, May 16\nWILLYS STEWARDS 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nAMVETS 7:30 P.M. Post Room\nNATIONAL SUPPLY ELEC. 9:00 A.M. Parlor B\nBARON STEEL 7:30 P.M. Parlor C\nSAM EARLEY 8:00 P.M. Parlor H","height":"26824","width":"19528"}}
